<p class="italic">Ask yourself if you can relate:<br><span class="h4" style="font-style:italic;">Your hair seems like it will only grow to a certain length and thickness - then it stops.</span></p>

<p>No matter how hard you've tried, it seems like you'll never be able to have the long, thick hair that it seems like it"s so easy for other people to get. Or maybe you've spent years growing your hair out, only to struggle with breakage, dryness and frizziness, or it becomes so unmanageable that you end up chopping it off again. (Only to fall into a "<a href="<?= $step1_link ?>" target="_blank">drastic haircut depression</a>" and start the cycle again!)</p>

<figure class="left"><a href="<?= $step1_link ?>" target="_blank"><img src="<?= $assets ?>/perfecthair_files/frizzy-hair.jpg" alt="Frizzy-hair" ondragstart="return false;"></a></figure>

<p>Well girlfriend, <span class="uppercase" style="font-size:1.1em;">let me be real with you</span> - These situations aren't in your imagination. It has always been extremely difficult (and for some, impossible) to grow long hair without resorting to painful hair extensions. This is because hair growth is largely influenced by age - as we age into our twenties and beyond, our bodies don't make the chemicals we need to grow healthy, thick hair - resulting in frail, dry hair that refuses to grow past our shoulders.</p>

<figure class="center text-center"><a href="<?= $step1_link ?>" target="_blank"><img src="<?= $assets ?>/perfecthair_files/measurements.jpg" alt="Measurements" ondragstart="return false;"></a></figure>
